{
  "card_id": "short_term_high_short_term_low",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Short-Term High / Short-Term Low",
  "aliases": [
    "Short-Term High",
    "short-term high",
    "Short-Term Low",
    "short-term low",
    "Short-Term Swing Low",
    "STH",
    "sth",
    "STH / STL",
    "STL",
    "stl",
    "Swing High / Swing Low"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "Minor swing points on the current time frame formed by adjacent candles: a short-term high has lower highs on both sides; a short-term low has higher lows on both sides. They represent external liquidity levels and are the smallest units in the fractal market structure, used to build intermediate and long-term levels.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Short-term high: current candle high is higher than the highs of the immediately preceding and following candles, i.e., lower highs on both sides.",
    "Short-term low: current candle low is lower than the lows of the immediately preceding and following candles, i.e., higher lows on both sides.",
    "Must have clear two-sided comparison; isolated extreme points are not valid.",
    "In an uptrend, identify alternating higher highs and higher lows; in a downtrend, lower highs and lower lows.",
    "Prioritize swing points associated with important price levels (e.g., order blocks, fair value gaps, previous day/week highs/lows).",
    "After a sweep, a price displacement and close beyond the relevant candle confirms the swing point and may turn that candle into an order block.",
    "Applicable on any timeframe; higher timeframe short-term highs/lows have higher priority.",
    "Multiple short-term highs/lows combine to form intermediate-term highs/lows.",
    "Flag a short-term high/low as relevant if the candle that closes through a series of opposing candles also wicks or closes beyond it.",
    "Distinguish basic adjacent-candle short-term highs/lows from more significant buy-side/sell-side liquidity levels.",
    "Treat the short-term high/low as taken when the continuation candle's range extends beyond it, not merely when price approaches.",
    "For short-term low: confirm its minor status by comparing to surrounding structure; it should not yet be flanked by other short-term lows on both sides (which would make it intermediate-term)."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Short-term highs/lows mark external liquidity zones (stop hunts). Use them to: (1) predict price targets for liquidity sweeps; (2) place stops beyond the swing point to reduce false triggers; (3) confirm market structure shifts when price breaks a prior swing point; (4) set profit targets. When a continuation setup sweeps a short-term high/low, do not enter immediately; wait for a fresh V-shaped recovery and closure through opposing candles. If price reverses after the sweep, treat it as manipulation and trade the opposite direction using that level as a new point of interest. On lower timeframe entries, a sweep of a short-term low followed by a close below confirms bearish continuation; enter on close or retest, stop above the candle high, target minimum 2R or higher timeframe objectives.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Entering immediately at a short-term high/low without waiting for confirmation (e.g., close beyond the swing or additional continuation), leading to stop-outs.",
    "Confusing a sweep of a short-term high/low with a valid protected swing reversal; sometimes price sweeps and continues in the original direction.",
    "Mistaking isolated extreme points or random local highs/lows for valid short-term highs/lows, ignoring the required two-sided structure.",
    "Selecting swing points unrelated to important price levels (order blocks, FVGs, previous key levels).",
    "Confusing short-term highs/lows with order blocks: the former are reference points, the latter are support/resistance zones from specific candles.",
    "Confusing short-term with intermediate-term highs/lows, leading to incorrect structural hierarchy.",
    "Trading before the swing point is validated by subsequent price action (e.g., right-side structure confirmation).",
    "Ignoring timeframe context: treating a low timeframe swing reversal as a high timeframe trend reversal, causing premature entries.",
    "Expecting a swept short-term high/low to continue providing support/resistance; instead look for internal liquidity or new order blocks.",
    "Failing to differentiate small adjacent-candle short-term highs from more significant buy-side/sell-side liquidity levels where reversals are more likely.",
    "Acting on a sweep alone without waiting for a close below (for short-term low) to confirm continuation."
  ],
